          <div class=3D"crayons-article__main ">
            <div class=3D"crayons-article__body text-styles spec__body" dat=
a-article-id=3D"1335867" id=3D"article-body">
                <p>I was working on a personal Go project when I needed the=
 ability to encrypt &amp; decrypt arbitrary pieces of data (strings or JSON=
 payloads or whatever) using a secret key. This article is the result of al=
l the learning I had in the last couple of days while trying to achieve tha=
t.</p>

<h2>
  <a name=3D"tldr" href=3D"https://dev.to/breda/secret-key-encryption-with-=
go-using-aes-316d#tldr">
  </a>
  TL;DR
</h2>

<p>Secret key (or Symmetric) encryption requires the use of a block cipher =
such as AES. AES by itself can only encrypt/decrypt 16 byte long data (whic=
h is its block size), hence the need to use a block cipher mode. </p>

<p>GCM block cipher mode is one of many modes. It is a method that uses AES=
 in a way that enables us to encrypt/decrypt arbitrary sized data. It also =
adds message authentication (integrity).</p>

<p>The complete working code example is <a href=3D"https://dev.to/breda/sec=
ret-key-encryption-with-go-using-aes-316d#code">here</a>.</p>

<h2>
  <a name=3D"a-cryptography-primer" href=3D"https://dev.to/breda/secret-key=
-encryption-with-go-using-aes-316d#a-cryptography-primer">
  </a>
  A Cryptography primer
</h2>

<p>Before diving in, I'd like to define some Cryptography terminology.</p>

<ul>
<li>A <code>secret key</code> is basically an agreed upon value between com=
municating parties (machines, you and your friends ... or any combination o=
f that).</li>
<li>
<code>Plaintext</code> is the text that you want to encrypt so that no one =
else can read it unless that someone has the secret key.</li>
<li>
<code>Ciphertext</code> is the encryption result of the plaintext.</li>
<li>A <code>cipher</code> is the algorithm that does the actual work of enc=
rypting and decrypting our data.</li>
</ul>

<p>What we are talking about here is called <code>Symmetric encryption</cod=
e> (also called <code>Secret key encryption</code>) whereby we use the same=
 key to encrypt our plaintext to  ciphertext and to revert the ciphertext b=
ack to plaintext.</p>

<h3>
  <a name=3D"cipher-types" href=3D"https://dev.to/breda/secret-key-encrypti=
on-with-go-using-aes-316d#cipher-types">
  </a>
  Cipher types
</h3>

<p>Now let's talk a bit about ciphers. Symmetric ciphers belong to two main=
 categories:</p>

<ul>
<li>Stream ciphers: operate by encrypting each bit (or byte) of the plainte=
xt at a time, producing the ciphertext.</li>
<li>and Block ciphers: operate by encrypting fixed-sized blocks of plaintex=
t.</li>
</ul>

<p>Stream and Block ciphers are the building blocks (no pun intended) of mo=
re complicated and siphisticated cryptographic utilities such as MACs, hash=
 functions, symmetric-key digital signature schemes and much more.</p>

<p>Now let's take one example of a Block cipher and dive more into it: AES,=
 Advanded Encryption Standard.</p>

<p>AES is a block cipher that takes a fixed-size key and fixed-size plainte=
xt, and returns fixed-size ciphertext. AES has three variants that are sele=
cted based on the secret key length, all of which <a href=3D"https://cs.ope=
nsource.google/go/go/+/refs/tags/go1.19.5:src/crypto/aes/cipher.go;l=3D15" =
target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">use a fixed-sized block of 16=
 bytes (or 128 bits)</a>.</p>

<div class=3D"table-wrapper-paragraph"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Secret Key Length</th>
<th>AES Variant</th>
<th>Block Size</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>16 bytes (128 bits)</td>
<td>AES-128</td>
<td>16 bytes (128 bits)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>24 bytes (192 bits)</td>
<td>AES-192</td>
<td>16 bytes (128 bits)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>32 bytes (25 6bits)</td>
<td>AES-256</td>
<td>16 bytes (128 bits)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>

<p>Because the block size of AES is set to 16 bytes, the plaintext must be =
at least 16 bytes long. Which causes a problem for us since we want to be a=
ble to encrypt/decrypt arbitrary sized data.</p>

<p>Let's put that aside for now and let's have a look at an example of encr=
ypting some data using AES.</p>

<p>Let's give it a try.<br>
</p>

